Co-optimization problem formulation
MasCOR’s primary task is stochastic co-optimization [xi2014stochastic] under region-specific renewable uncertainty, while constraining the probability of positive carbon emissions (Fig. 1 (b)). To enable reliable power-to-methanolsystem design and operation, MasCOR adopts a scenario-based bilevel optimization framework [sinha2017review, dempe2002foundations]. The first stage determines the system design, while the second stage solves dynamic operational problems under a given design.
Let denote a set of scenarios over a time horizon of length , where each scenario
represents a realization of renewable power and grid price. The scenario set is sampled from a known continuous probability density function .
For a given design vector (see Supplementary Note 3.1 for definition), the second-stage problem solves a monthly operational optimization for each scenario . The objective is to maximize operational profit (Eq. 1) while minimizing net carbon emissions (Eq. 2), subject to hourly operational constraints (Eqs. 3, 5 and 6), as detailed in Supplementary Note 1.2. The resulting operational decisions yield the LCOM, , and the net carbon emission, . A sample-average approximation is used to estimate the expected LCOM and carbon emission, as well as the probability of positive carbon emissions.
The first-stage problem then optimizes the system design by minimizing the expected LCOM and carbon emissions, subject to a constraint that limits the probability of positive carbon emissions to a prescribed threshold .
