An actor-critic ML model for offline RL of oracle trajectories
We adopt a decision transformer (DT) [chen2021decision] as the backbone and built an actor–critic structure [barto2012neuronlike, konda1999actor]: the actor predict the next action under a given historical trajectory (Eq. 48), conditioned on two goal tokens (, ), while the critic predicts next goals () under a given historical operational trajectory (Eq. 49). By updating the goal with feedback received from the critic, the actor model tracks near-optimal trajectories over extended horizons. However, optimal trajectories vary drastically across system designs and renewable scenarios; therefore, conditioning the actor policy solely on and limits generalization, which is essential for co-optimization. To address this, we introduced two conditional tokens: a design token and a renewable-trend token . The design token encodes the normalized design vector , while the renewable-trend token compresses the 576-hr time series into 24-hr averages. By combining these conditional tokens with the goal tokens (, ), the agent adapts its policy to diverse designs and renewable patterns, thereby improving generalization. Using this improved setup, we trained an offline actor–critic RL agent on the oracle dataset to learn distributions over actions and corresponding future cumulative profit and carbon emission goals.
